Loading in data via xlsx.

Use a similar function to read xlsx (Excel) files instead.

ci_np <- read_excel(here("data", "ci_np.xlsx"))

**If the file type is known, you can use read_xlsx() or read_xls() as well.

Making our first ggplot - Visitors to Channel Islands NP

What to tell R 1. We are using the function ggplot() 2. What data were using and what variables will be plot 3. The type of graph we are going to plot on (i.e.dot, line, column/bar)

Generic form: ggplot(data = df_name, aes(x = x_var_name, y = y_var_name)) + geom_type()

Here is a plot of visitors to Channel Islands NP over time:

ggplot(data = ci_np, aes(x = year, y = visitors)) +
  geom_line()

Were going to set it as object named geom_base so we can modify/add-on.

geom_base <- ggplot(data = ci_np, aes(x = year, y = visitors))

We can change the plot type by using + geom_type().

geom_base +
  geom_point()

geom_base +
  geom_col()

geom_base +
  geom_area()

Customizing ggplot plots

Aesthetics

Aesthetics can be modified by adding arguments to the geom_type() function. These include: - color = or colour = : update point or line colors

  • fill = : update fill color for objects with areas

  • linetype = : update the line type (dashed, long dash, etc.)

  • pch = : update the point style

  • size = : update the element size (e.g.of points or line thickness)

  • alpha = : update element opacity (1 = opaque, 0 = transparent)

Lets make our plot a line plot with purple, dashed lines.

geom_base +
  geom_line(
    color = "purple",
    linetype = "dashed"
  )

### Mapping variables onto aesthetics Variables can also be mapped onto aesthetics. For example, changing the shading of a point depending on a different variable. These variables should be placed inside the aes() function inside of a geom_type() function: - geom_type(aes(size = var_name, etc.))

geom_base +
  geom_point(
    aes(size = visitors,
        color = visitors),
    alpha = 0.6
  )
